<paragraph id="FB660E295D441B7ADF3DFE70FBB2FDDD" blockId="4.[264,1324,436,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Recently a new species of 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADC7DFE70FD19FE7E" box="[584,717,436,461]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Meramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADC7DFE70FD19FE7E" box="[584,717,436,461]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Meramecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described based on one female specimen collected in Salta province, 
<collectingCountry id="83CE4EB95D441B7ADC75FE18FD61FE45" box="[576,693,476,502]" name="Argentina" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="9F4873D85D441B7ADCFFFE18FC4EFE45" author="Fernandez" box="[714,922,476,502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="6" refString="Fernandez, H. R. (2001) Acaros hiporreicos de Argentina: Nuevos Datos sobre Neomamersinae Lundblad. Physis, Secc. B, 58 (134 - 135): 21 - 28." type="journal article" year="2001">
Fernández, 
<number id="4D111C0E5D441B7ADD6FFE18FC4EFE45" box="[858,922,476,502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). After the study of the original description (
<bibRefCitation id="9F4873D85D441B7ADF97FDC0FD12FDAD" author="Smith" box="[418,710,516,542]" pageId="4" pageNumber="6" refString="Smith I. M. &amp; Cook, D. R. (1994). North American species of Neomamersinae Lundblad (Acari: Hydrachnidia: Limnesiidae). Canadian Entomologist, 126, 1131 - 1184" type="journal article" year="1994">
Smith and Cook, 
<number id="4D111C0E5D441B7ADCBFFDC0FD12FDAD" box="[650,710,516,542]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1994.0">1994</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADD82FDC0FBA0FDAE" box="[951,1140,516,541]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Parameramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADD82FDC0FBA0FDAE" box="[951,1140,516,541]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Parameramecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Arizona (
<collectingCountry id="83CE4EB95D441B7ADF27FDE8FEB7FDF5" box="[274,355,556,582]" name="United States of America" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">U.S.A.</collectingCountry>
) and comparison of 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADC6AFDE8FD39FDF6" box="[607,749,556,581]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Meramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saltensis">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADC6AFDE8FD39FDF6" box="[607,749,556,581]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. saltensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADD00FDE8FB39FDF5" authority="Smith and Cook, I" authorityName="Smith and Cook, I" box="[821,1261,556,582]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Meramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multipora" subGenus="Parameramecia">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADD00FDE8FBD1FDF6" box="[821,1029,556,581]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. (P.) multipora</emphasis>
Smith and Cook, I
</taxonomicName>
conclude that 
<collectingCountry id="83CE4EB95D441B7ADFB7FD90FDF5FDDD" box="[386,545,596,622]" name="Argentina" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">the Argentine</collectingCountry>
species fits well within the subgenus description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B3C35DA25D441B7ADF0DFDB8FB0FFBC5" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="description">
<paragraph id="FB660E295D441B7ADF0DFDB8FB86FD55" blockId="4.[264,1324,436,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The inclusion of the new species from Salta requires a revision of the diagnosis of the subgenus 
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADF4AFD60FD90FD0E" box="[383,580,676,701]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADF4AFD60FD94FD0E" box="[383,576,676,701]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Parameramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Parameramecia</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Acetabula number should be expanded as follows: 
<quantity id="3C21A3CC5D441B7ADA81FD60FB28FD0D" box="[1204,1276,676,702]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" metricValueMax="2.032" metricValueMin="1.016" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="in" value="6.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="4.0">4­8 in</quantity>
the anterior group, 
<quantity id="3C21A3CC5D441B7ADF88FD08FDD6FD55" box="[445,514,716,742]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.397" metricValueMax="1.778" metricValueMin="1.016" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="in" value="5.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="4.0">4­7 in</quantity>
the middle group, and 
<quantity id="3C21A3CC5D441B7ADD27FD08FCB0FD55" box="[786,868,716,742]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.032" metricValueMax="2.794" metricValueMin="1.27" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="in" value="8.0" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="5.0">5­11 in</quantity>
the posterior group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB660E295D441B7ADF0DFD30FDFDFCED" blockId="4.[264,1324,436,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
A good character for differentiating members of the subgenera 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADA5EFD30FB25FCBE" box="[1131,1265,756,781]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Meramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADA5EFD30FB25FCBE" box="[1131,1265,756,781]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Meramecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADF3DFCD8FE11FC86" box="[264,453,796,821]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Parameramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADF3DFCD8FE11FC86" box="[264,453,796,821]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Parameramecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the size of the peg like seta on P­II, which is much more robust in 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADF3DFC80FE10FCEE" box="[264,452,836,861]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Parameramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADF3DFC80FE10FCEE" box="[264,452,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Parameramecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB660E295D441B7ADF0DFCA8FB0FFBC5" blockId="4.[264,1324,436,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
In contrast, the ventral P­IV setae seem to be variable in length among 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADABDFCA8FEF8FC1E" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Parameramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADABDFCA8FEF8FC1E" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Parameramecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. Likewise, in 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADC1AFC50FCF5FC1E" box="[559,801,916,941]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Meramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saltensis">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADC1AFC50FCF5FC1E" box="[559,801,916,941]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Meramecia saltensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the thick ventral setae on tibiae of legs I are located distally, while in 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADC0CFC78FD03FC66" box="[569,727,956,981]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Meramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multipora">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADC0CFC78FD03FC66" box="[569,727,956,981]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. multipora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are located near the middle of the segment. Thus, the location of these setae is not a good character for differentiating between subgenera as proposed 
<bibRefCitation id="9F4873D85D441B7ADFC1FBC8FCC4FB95" author="Smith" box="[500,784,1036,1062]" pageId="4" pageNumber="6" refString="Smith I. M. &amp; Cook, D. R. (1994). North American species of Neomamersinae Lundblad (Acari: Hydrachnidia: Limnesiidae). Canadian Entomologist, 126, 1131 - 1184" type="journal article" year="1994">
Smith and Cook (
<number id="4D111C0E5D441B7ADCF3FBC8FCD2FB95" box="[710,774,1036,1062]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1994.0">1994</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. Finally, the legs of 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADA34FBC8FB5BFB96" box="[1025,1167,1036,1061]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Meramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saltensis">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADA34FBC8FB5BFB96" box="[1025,1167,1036,1061]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. saltensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have setiferous blade­like spines as do members of the 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADD24FBF0FC43FBFE" box="[785,919,1076,1101]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Meramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADD24FBF0FC43FBFE" box="[785,919,1076,1101]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Meramecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgenus. The spines of this 
<typeStatus id="2462B08B5D441B7ADACDFBF0FAFFFBFD" box="[1272,1323,1076,1102]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">type</typeStatus>
are absent in other 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADFD2FB98FD70FBC6" box="[487,676,1116,1141]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Parameramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADFD2FB98FD70FBC6" box="[487,676,1116,1141]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Parameramecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, being autopomorphic for 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADA0CFB98FB00FBC6" box="[1081,1236,1116,1141]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Meramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multipora">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADA0CFB98FB00FBC6" box="[1081,1236,1116,1141]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. multipora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B3C35DA25D441B7ADF0DFB40FDB4FB5D" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FB660E295D441B7ADF0DFB40FDB4FB5D" blockId="4.[264,1324,436,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADF0DFB40FE4AFB2E" box="[312,414,1156,1181]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Remarks</emphasis>
: The geographic distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="3CD975AA5D441B7ADD05FB40FC39FB2E" box="[816,1005,1156,1181]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Parameramecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9ADD23B5D441B7ADD05FB40FC39FB2E" box="[816,1005,1156,1181]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Parameramecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is disjunct (
<collectingCountry id="83CE4EB95D441B7ADAB2FB40FAFFFB2D" box="[1159,1323,1156,1182]" name="United States of America" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">United States</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="83CE4EB95D441B7ADF0FFB68FE61FB75" box="[314,437,1196,1222]" name="Argentina" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Argentina</collectingCountry>
). However, this distribution may be a result of the absence of collections in the Neotropics (
<bibRefCitation id="9F4873D85D441B7ADFF1FB10FD87FB5D" author="Cook" box="[452,595,1236,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refString="Cook, D. R. (1980) Neotropical Water Mites. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 31, 1 - 645." type="journal article" year="1980">
Cook, 
<number id="4D111C0E5D441B7ADC21FB10FD87FB5D" box="[532,595,1236,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1980.0">1980</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
